definition.value: A citrate(2-) that is the dianion obtained by the deprotonation of the terminal carboxy groups of citric acid.
A member of the class of benzimidazoles that is fenbendazole in which the sulfur has been oxidised to the corresponding sulfoxide.
A substance that suppresses Mycobacterium leprae, ameliorates the clinical manifestations of leprosy, and/or reduces the incidence and severity of leprous reactions.
An agent useful in the treatment or prevention of coccidiosis in man or animals.

Any fatty acid in which the parent hydrocarbon chain has one or more alkyl substituents; a common component in animal and bacterial lipids. The fatty acyl chain is usually saturated and the substituent a methyl group; however, unsaturated BCFAs are found in marine animals, and branches other than methyl are found in microbial lipids.
Any antimicrobial drug which is used to treat or prevent protozoal infections.
A substance used to lower plasma cholesterol levels.
A 2-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is acetic acid in which two of the methyl hydrogens are substituted by phenyl and hydroxyl groups.
A gout suppressant that acts directly on the renal tubule to increase the excretion of uric acid, thus reducing its concentrations in plasma.
A drug used to treat rheumatoid arthritis.
A drug that increases uric acid excretion by the kidney (uricosuric drug), decreases uric acid production (antihyperuricemic), or alleviates the pain and inflammation of acute attacks of gout.
A drug used for its effect on the kidneys' regulation of body fluid composition and volume.
An organosulfur compound having the structure RS(=O)2R (R =/= H).
Any alpha-amino acid ester that has L-valine as the amino acid component.

A compound or agent that combines with lipoxygenase and thereby prevents its substrate-enzyme combination with arachidonic acid and the formation of the icosanoid products hydroxyicosatetraenoic acid and various leukotrienes.

A homodetic cyclic peptide consisting of (4R)-2-[(1S,2S)-1-amino-2-methylbutyl]-4,5-dihydro-1,3-thiazole-4-carboxylic acid attached head-to-tail to L-leucyl,D-glutamyl, L-lysyl, D-ornityl, L-isoleucyl, D-phenylalanyl, L-histidyl. D-aspartyl and L-asparaginyl residues coupled in sequence and cyclised by condensation of the side-chain amino group of the L-lysyl residue with the C-terminal carboxylic acid group. It is the major component of bacitracin.
Any monocarboxylic acid which also contains a separate (alcoholic or phenolic) hydroxy substituent.
Any monocarboxylic acid having at least one additional oxo functional group.
Anhydrides derived from carboxylic acids.
Any carboxylic acid anion containing at least one oxo group.
A dicarboxylic acid monoanion that is the conjugate base of glutaric acid.
Any monocarboxylic acid having a 2-oxo substituent.
A steroid ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of any carboxylic acid with the 3-hydroxy group of a sterol.
A monosubstitution product of hydrogen peroxide, HOOH.
Monosubstitution products of hydrogen peroxide HOOH, having the skeleton ROOH, in which R is any organyl group.
A non-proteinogenic amino acid in which the amino group is located on the carbon atom at the position delta to the carboxy group.

An agent that has an affinity for serotonin receptors and is able to mimic the effects of serotonin by stimulating the physiologic activity at the cell receptors. Serotonin agonists are used as antidepressants, anxiolytics, and in the treatment of migraine disorders.

A substance used for its pharmacological action on any aspect of neurotransmitter systems. Neurotransmitter agents include agonists, antagonists, degradation inhibitors, uptake inhibitors, depleters, precursors, and modulators of receptor function.
An amino acid in which the amino group is located on the carbon atom at the position epsilon to the carboxy group.
A hexadienoic acid with double bonds at C-2 and C-4; it has four geometrical isomers, of which the trans,trans-form is naturally occurring.
A pentadienoic acid with the double bonds at positions 2 and 4.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that has a hydroxy group beta to the carboxy group.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid which has a hydroxy group located gamma to the carboxy group.
Any  hydroxy monocarboxylic acid carrying at least two hydroxy groups.
An oxo monocarboxylic acid anion having the oxo group located at the 3-position (R = H or organyl group).
Any amino acid carrying two amino groups.
A polycyclic compound that contains more than one ring with at least two common atoms (also known as bridgehead carbons) that are not adjacent to each other.
Natural and synthetic antibiotics containing the 4-thia-1-azabicyclo[3.2.0]heptan-7-one structure, generally assumed to have the 5R configuration unless otherwise specified.
A straight chain alkane containing 13 carbon atoms. It forms a component of the essential oils isolated from plants such as Abelmoschus esculentus.
Any C22 polyunsaturated fatty acid containing six double bonds.
